"""
Context Layer — 2 Chronicles chapters 13–17
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-2chronicles-13-17.py

Ch13: Abijah's war against Jeroboam; unique Chronicler speech; salt covenant.
Ch14: Asa's early reform; battle against Zerah the Cushite.
Ch15: Azariah's prophecy; covenant renewal; Maacah deposed.
Ch16: Asa's failure — Syrian alliance; Hanani imprisoned; doctors instead of YHWH.
Ch17: Jehoshaphat's righteous beginning; law-teaching mission throughout Judah.
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON2_CONTEXT_13_17 = {
  "13": {
    "1": "<p>In the eighteenth year of King Jeroboam, Abijah begins to reign over Judah. The synchronization with the northern king&rsquo;s regnal year (a device borrowed from Kings) places Abijah in the broader political landscape: he faces the most powerful northern king (Jeroboam reigned 22 years, 1 Kgs 14:20) at a moment of southern-kingdom transition. 1 Kings 15:1-8 gives Abijah only 8 verses and a negative evaluation; 2 Chronicles devotes 22 verses to him and presents a positive picture, centering on his theological speech at Mount Zemaraim.</p>",
    "2": "<p>His mother was Micaiah the daughter of Uriel of Gibeah. The parallel in 1 Kgs 15:2 gives the mother&rsquo;s name as Maacah daughter of Abishalom — a discrepancy that has generated discussion. The most likely explanation is that Maacah and Micaiah are variant name forms for the same woman, or that Uriel and Abishalom (possibly Absalom) are different members of the maternal family line. Gibeah, a Benjaminite city, is Saul&rsquo;s home city — a subtle reminder that the southern monarchy drew from diverse Israelite ancestry.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Abijah draws up 400,000 chosen warriors; Jeroboam faces him with 800,000 chosen warriors. The 2:1 numerical disadvantage for Judah — before the battle even begins — sets up the Chronicler&rsquo;s holy-war narrative: the smaller force wins through YHWH&rsquo;s intervention, not military might. The numbers are theological rather than census-precise; they establish the scale of the opposition that divine power will overcome.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Abijah stands on Mount Zemaraim in the hill country of Ephraim and delivers his speech. The location — Ephraim&rsquo;s hill country, technically northern territory — is audacious: Abijah addresses the enemy from their own terrain before battle. The speech (vv4-12) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most distinctive addition to the parallel Kings account; it functions as a theological manifesto for the Davidic covenant against the apostate north.</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>Hălōʾ lāḵem lāḏaʿat kî YHWH ʾĕlōhê Yiśrāʾēl nātan mamlāḵāh lᵉḏāwîḏ ʿal-Yiśrāʾēl lᵉʿôlām lô ûlᵉḇānāyw bᵉrît melaḥ</em> — &ldquo;Ought you not to know that the LORD God of Israel gave the kingship over Israel forever to David and his sons by a covenant of salt?&rdquo; The &ldquo;covenant of salt&rdquo; (<em>bᵉrît melaḥ</em>) is an ancient Near Eastern idiom for a permanent, incorruptible covenant — salt does not decay. The phrase appears in Lev 2:13 (salt with every grain offering) and Num 18:19 (a salt covenant for the priestly allotment). Applied to the Davidic covenant, it asserts absolute irrevocability.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Yet Jeroboam son of Nebat, a servant of Solomon, rose up and rebelled against his lord. The Chronicler characterizes the northern kingdom&rsquo;s founding as rebellion (<em>wayyiqōm... wayyimrōḏ</em>) against a legitimate covenantal order. Jeroboam is identified as Solomon&rsquo;s servant — his political legitimacy is derivative, not original. The theological charge is not mere political commentary but covenant theology: the schism was apostasy from YHWH&rsquo;s established order.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Worthless men (<em>ʾănāšîm rêqîm</em>) gathered around Jeroboam and defied Rehoboam when he was young and irresolutehearted (<em>wᵉrōḵ lēḇāḇ</em>). The description of Rehoboam as <em>rōḵ</em> (tender/weak) and <em>naʿar</em> (young) at the time of the schism gives a partial excuse for his failure while retaining Jeroboam&rsquo;s culpability. The &ldquo;worthless men&rdquo; who facilitated the split are <em>ʾănāšîm rêqîm</em> — men of emptiness, the same epithet used in Judg 9:4 and 11:3 for disreputable followers.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Now you think you can withstand the kingdom of YHWH in the hand of the sons of David — <em>mamleket YHWH bᵉyaḏ bᵉnê ḏāwîḏ</em>. The phrase &ldquo;kingdom of YHWH&rdquo; is distinctive: the Davidic monarchy is not merely the kingdom of Israel or the kingdom of Judah; it is YHWH&rsquo;s own kingdom expressed through David&rsquo;s house. You are many — Abijah concedes the numerical superiority — but you have with you the golden calves that Jeroboam made you for gods (<em>lēʾlōhîm</em>).</p>",
    "9": "<p>The northern kingdom expelled the Levitical priests and made priests like the peoples of other lands — <em>kᵉʿammê hāʾărāṣôt</em>. Whoever came to consecrate himself with a young bull and seven rams became a priest of what are not gods (<em>lōʾ ʾĕlōhîm</em>). Jeroboam&rsquo;s non-Levitical priesthood (1 Kgs 12:31: &ldquo;he made priests from among all the people&rdquo;) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s central charge against the north: the liturgical legitimacy is gone. The proper succession from Aaron through Levi is broken; the north&rsquo;s worship is therefore illegitimate.</p>",
    "10": "<p>As for us, YHWH is our God, and we have not forsaken him. The sons of Aaron are our priests who minister to YHWH, and Levites serve in their appointed work. They burn to YHWH morning and evening burnt offerings and fragrant incense — <em>bōqer bōqer ûḇāʿereḇ ʿāreḇ ʿōlôt ûqᵉṭōret sammîm</em>. The morning-and-evening offering schedule (Exod 29:38-42; Num 28:3-8) is the mark of legitimate continuous worship. The perpetual smoke rising from the Jerusalem temple is Abijah&rsquo;s proof of covenantal continuity.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Showbread is set on the table, the golden lampstand and its lamps burn every evening — <em>bᵉḵol-ʿereḇ ʿāreḇ</em>. The three items specified — burnt offerings, incense, showbread, lampstand — are all Mosaic requirements for the tabernacle (Exod 25:23-40; 30:7-8; Lev 24:5-9). For us we keep the guard of YHWH our God, but you have forsaken him. The contrast is liturgical-theological: Judah maintains the divine pattern; Israel has abandoned it.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Behold, God is with us at our head, and his priests with their battle trumpets (<em>ḥaṣôṣᵉrôt hattᵉrûʿāh</em>) to sound the battle alarm against you. Sons of Israel, do not fight against YHWH, the God of your fathers, for you cannot succeed. The Mosaic battle-trumpet (Num 10:9) deployed in holy war is the signal that this battle is YHWH&rsquo;s own — the trumpets summon divine aid as much as announce military action. The final warning — &ldquo;you cannot succeed (<em>lōʾ taṣlîḥû</em>)&rdquo; — uses the Chronicler&rsquo;s covenant-success vocabulary against Jeroboam.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Jeroboam sends an ambush around behind the Judahite force while he faces them in front — a pincer movement designed to encircle and destroy. The military tactic mirrors the spiritual condition of the north: deception, ambush, double-dealing. Judah faces the enemy in front and an ambush from behind — the position of utter military vulnerability that makes YHWH&rsquo;s deliverance all the more spectacular.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Judah turns and sees the battle in front and behind — they cry to YHWH (<em>wayyizʿăqû lYHWH</em>) and the priests sound their trumpets. The instinct to cry out to YHWH in extremity is the Chronicler&rsquo;s recurring mark of covenant faithfulness: Asa (14:11), Jehoshaphat (18:31; 20:3-4), and now Abijah. The same battle-trumpet that announced the engagement (v12) is now blown in prayer — the military and liturgical fused in the moment of crisis.</p>",
    "15": "<p>As the men of Judah shouted, God defeated Jeroboam and all Israel before Abijah and Judah. The victory is attributed entirely to God (<em>ʾĕlōhîm hikkāh ʾet-Yarāḇᵉʿām wᵉḵol-Yiśrāʾēl liphᵉnê ʾAḇiyyāh wîhûḏāh</em>) — YHWH&rsquo;s defeat of the north at the moment of the Judahite battle cry. The military narrative dissolves into theological narrative: the war cry is the turning point, not the tactical maneuver.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Israelites flee before Judah — God delivers them into their hand. The passive form (<em>wayyibbᵉrᵉḥû... wayyittᵉnēm ʾĕlōhîm bᵉyāḏām</em>) maintains the theological emphasis: the fleeing is Israel&rsquo;s action; the deliverance is God&rsquo;s. The distinction is the Chronicler&rsquo;s consistent refusal to credit human military prowess for covenant victories.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Abijah and his people strike down 500,000 chosen men of Israel. The devastating toll — half the northern army — is a theological number signaling the completeness of the northern defeat. The Chronicler is not providing a body count for the military historian; he is asserting that YHWH&rsquo;s judgment on covenant-breakers is comprehensive. No northern force of this magnitude escaped.</p>",
    "18": "<p>At that time the men of Israel were subdued, and the people of Judah prevailed, because they relied on YHWH (<em>kî nišʿănû ʿal-YHWH</em>). The explanatory formula is the Chronicler&rsquo;s theological summary of the battle: the reliance on YHWH (<em>šāʿan</em> = to lean/trust) is the causal factor in the victory. The same verb will describe Asa&rsquo;s later failure: in ch16, when Asa relies on Syria instead of YHWH, he receives a rebuke using this exact word.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Abijah pursues Jeroboam and captures several cities — Bethel, Jeshanah, Ephron — with their villages. The capture of Bethel is historically significant: Bethel was Jeroboam I&rsquo;s primary golden calf shrine (1 Kgs 12:29). For Abijah to capture Bethel, even temporarily, is a symbolic victory over the north&rsquo;s apostate cult. The city will revert to the north after Abijah&rsquo;s short reign, but the capture signals the theological bankruptcy of Jeroboam&rsquo;s religious establishment.</p>",
    "20": "<p>Jeroboam did not regain power in the days of Abijah — YHWH struck him (<em>wayyiggᵉpēhû YHWH</em>) and he died. The death of Jeroboam as divine act — not attributed to military defeat or natural causes but to direct divine judgment — is the Chronicler&rsquo;s verdict on the apostate founder of the northern kingdom. 1 Kings 14:20 simply says he &ldquo;lay down with his fathers&rdquo; after 22 years; Chronicles interprets this as divine execution.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Abijah grew mighty. He had fourteen wives and fathered 22 sons and 16 daughters. The fertility formula signals divine blessing — large family as evidence of covenant favor. In the ancient world (and in the Chronicler&rsquo;s worldview), numerous progeny was not an embarrassing detail but a mark of God&rsquo;s blessing on the covenantal line. The 22 sons and 16 daughters ensure the Davidic succession continues.</p>",
    "22": "<p>The rest of the acts of Abijah, his ways and his words, are written in the midrash (<em>bᵉmiḏraš</em>) of the prophet Iddo. The Chronicler cites &ldquo;midrash&rdquo; (<em>midrāš</em>) as a source — the only use of this term in the Hebrew Bible in a historiographical sense (also 24:27). The word means &ldquo;exposition/inquiry/study&rdquo; — a prophetic study or commentary associated with Iddo. The Chronicler draws on prophetic-homiletical literature alongside royal annals.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Abijah rested with his fathers and was buried in the city of David. His son Asa reigned in his place. In his days the land had rest for ten years. The ten years of rest (<em>šāqᵉṭāh hāʾāreṣ ʿeśer šānîm</em>) under Asa&rsquo;s early reign is the Chronicler&rsquo;s thematic bridge: Abijah&rsquo;s victory over Jeroboam created conditions for Asa&rsquo;s extended peace. The rest-as-covenant-reward theme will run through ch14.</p>"
  },
  "14": {
    "1": "<p>Asa did what was good and right in the eyes of YHWH his God — <em>wayyaʿaś ʾAsāʾ haṭṭôḇ wᵉhayyāšār bᵉʿênê YHWH ʾĕlōhāyw</em>. The double evaluation formula (&ldquo;good and right&rdquo;) appears in Deuteronomy as the ideal covenantal obedience (Deut 6:18; 12:28) and in Chronicles for the best kings (2 Chr 31:20; Hezekiah). Asa&rsquo;s reign (910-869 BC, 41 years) is the longest of the good-king reigns in Chronicles.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Asa removes the foreign altars and the high places, breaks down the pillars (<em>massēḇôt</em>), cuts down the Asherim. The threefold destruction — altars, pillars, Asherim — targets the three most common forms of Canaanite cult infrastructure. <em>Massēḇôt</em> (standing stones/pillars) could be legitimate YHWH worship markers in early Israel (Gen 28:18; Exod 24:4) but became associated with Baalism and were prohibited (Deut 16:22); Asa breaks them. <em>ʾĂšērîm</em> (sacred poles or trees associated with the goddess Asherah) are cut down throughout the reform narratives.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Asa commanded Judah to seek YHWH (<em>liḏrôš ʾet-YHWH</em>) and to keep the law and the commandment. The command to seek YHWH is the Chronicler&rsquo;s foundational covenantal instruction — the same <em>dāraš</em> that will characterize every good king and whose absence characterizes every failed king. The conjunction of seeking YHWH and keeping Torah is the Chronicler&rsquo;s version of the Shema&rsquo;s call: love YHWH and keep his commands.</p>",
    "4": "<p>He also removed the high places and the incense altars from all the cities of Judah — <em>habbāmôt wᵉhammᵉḥammānîm</em>. The <em>mᵉḥammānîm</em> (incense altars or sun-pillars) are a distinctly Chronicler-preferred term (also in 2 Chr 34:4, 7; Lev 26:30; Isa 17:8; 27:9) for a type of illicit cult installation. And the kingdom had rest under him. The causal link — reform followed by rest — is the Chronicler&rsquo;s thesis statement for the reign: obedience produces <em>šeqeṭ</em> (quietness/rest).</p>",
    "5": "<p><em>Wayyiḇen ʿārê mibṣār bîhûḏāh kî šāqᵉṭāh hāʾāreṣ wᵉʾên-mᵉlāmāh bašššānîm hāhēm kî-hēnîaḥ YHWH lô</em> — He built fortified cities in Judah while the land was quiet and there was no war against him, for the LORD gave him peace (<em>hēnîaḥ lô</em>). The building of fortifications during peace is strategic preparation from a position of strength — using the gift of rest to create infrastructure for future defense. The <em>hēnîaḥ YHWH lô</em> (YHWH gave him rest) explicitly attributes the peace to divine gift, not military achievement.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Asa says to Judah: &ldquo;Let us build these cities and surround them with walls and towers, gates and bars. The land is still ours because we have sought the LORD our God (<em>dāraštānû ʾet-YHWH ʾĕlōhênû</em>); we have sought him, and he has given us peace on every side.&rdquo; The king&rsquo;s speech connects building activity to the prior act of <em>dāraš</em> — the infrastructure of defense is understood as the fruit of covenant faithfulness, not the cause of security. Security comes from YHWH; buildings are its expression.</p>",
    "7": "<p>So they built and prospered (<em>wayyiḇnû wayyaṣlîḥû</em>). Asa&rsquo;s army: 300,000 from Judah bearing large shields and spears (<em>ṣinnāh wᵉrōmaḥ</em>); 280,000 from Benjamin bearing small shields and bows. The tribal breakdown — Judah with heavy infantry weapons (large shield + spear), Benjamin with ranged weapons (small shield + bow) — reflects historical tribal military specializations. The total of 580,000 is Judah&rsquo;s fighting force at the height of Asa&rsquo;s early reign.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Zerah the Cushite comes out against them with an army of 1,000,000 (<em>ʾelep ʾălāpîm</em> — a thousand thousands) and 300 chariots and comes to Mareshah. Zerah is identified as a Cushite (<em>Kûšî</em>) — possibly an Egyptian commander of Nubian (Cushite) troops, or an otherwise unknown African general. The ratio of 580,000 (Israel) to 1,000,000 (Cushite) is nearly 2:1 against Judah, establishing the holy-war context: victory will require divine rather than human military superiority.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Asa went out against him — in the Valley of Zephathah at Mareshah. Mareshah is in the Shephelah (foothills) southwest of Jerusalem — strategically significant as the entry point to the Judahite heartland from the southwest. To lose at Mareshah would expose Jerusalem itself. Asa&rsquo;s decision to meet the Cushites in the valley rather than retreat to defended cities reflects either military confidence or the holy-war posture of advancing with YHWH.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Asa cries to YHWH his God: <em>YHWH ʾên-ʿimmᵉḵā laʿăzōr bên-rāḇ lᵉʾên kōaḥ ʿăzrēnû YHWH ʾĕlōhênû kî-ʿāleḵā nišʿānnû ûḇᵉšimḵā-bānû ʿal-hehāmôn hazzeh YHWH ʾĕlōhênû ʾattāh ʾal-yaʿăṣōr ʿimmᵉḵā ʾĕnôš</em> — &ldquo;O LORD, there is none like you to help, between the mighty and the weak. Help us, O LORD our God, for we rely on you, and in your name we have come against this multitude. O LORD, you are our God; let not man prevail against you.&rdquo; The prayer names four elements: divine incomparability, divine help available to both strong and weak, human trust in the divine name, and the framing of the battle as YHWH vs. man (not Israel vs. Cushites).</p>",
    "11": "<p>YHWH defeats the Cushites before Asa and before Judah, and the Cushites flee. <em>Wayyiggōp YHWH ʾet-hakḵûšîm</em> — the LORD struck down the Cushites. The divine agent of defeat is explicit: this is not Asa&rsquo;s tactical brilliance but YHWH&rsquo;s direct intervention. The battle is narrated in a single verse — because the narrative is not really about the battle but about what preceded it (the prayer) and follows it (the reform).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Asa and the people with him pursue them as far as Gerar — <em>ʿaḏ-Gerār</em> — and the Cushites fall until none survive, for they were broken before YHWH and his army (<em>liḇnê YHWH wᵉlaḥayyālô</em>). The victorious army is described as &ldquo;YHWH&rsquo;s army&rdquo; — the designation given to Joshua (Josh 5:14-15) and to Israel in the Exodus (Exod 12:41). The human army is YHWH&rsquo;s army because it is fighting in YHWH&rsquo;s name and by YHWH&rsquo;s power.</p>",
    "13": "<p>They strike down all the cities around Gerar — the Philistine-adjacent territory — for the fear of YHWH comes upon them. The regional ripple effect of YHWH&rsquo;s victory on behalf of Judah — surrounding territories falling to the terror of YHWH (<em>paḥaḏ YHWH</em>) — is the same phenomenon described in the conquest narratives (Josh 2:9; 10:2) and in Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s era (2 Chr 17:10; 20:29). YHWH&rsquo;s visible intervention creates a sphere of divine fear that extends beyond the battlefield.</p>",
    "14": "<p>They plunder all the cities (for there was much plunder in them) and they strike down the tents of cattle-keepers and carry away sheep in abundance and camels. The spoil of the Cushite campaign is agricultural wealth (flocks and herds) — indicating the campaign reaches into the pastoral hinterlands of Gerar. The abundance of spoil is the Chronicler&rsquo;s sign of divine blessing: the one who fights for YHWH is enriched by YHWH.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Then Asa and all Judah and Benjamin return to Jerusalem. The return to Jerusalem — the covenantal center — closes the campaign narrative. The circuit is complete: the people leave Jerusalem trusting YHWH, fight in his name, win by his power, and return to the city of YHWH&rsquo;s dwelling. The geographical movement embodies the theological movement of the Chronicler&rsquo;s ideal: seek YHWH → go out → win → return and give thanks.</p>"
  },
  "15": {
    "1": "<p>The Spirit of God (<em>rûaḥ ʾĕlōhîm</em>) comes upon Azariah son of Oded. The prophetic Spirit clothing a human agent is the standard formula for OT prophetic inspiration (1 Chr 12:18; 2 Chr 20:14; Judg 6:34). Azariah son of Oded is otherwise unknown — the Chronicler often introduces minor prophetic figures who speak crucial theological words and then disappear from the record. This anonymity underscores that the word&rsquo;s authority comes from its divine source, not the prophet&rsquo;s status.</p>",
    "2": "<p><em>Šimʿûnî ʾAsāʾ wᵉḵol-Yᵉhûḏāh wBinyāmin YHWH ʿimmᵉḵem bihyôtḵem ʿimmô wᵉʾim-tiḏrᵉšûhû yimmāṣēʾ lāḵem wᵉʾim-taʿăzᵉḇûhû yaʿăzōḇ ʾetḵem</em> — &ldquo;Hear me, Asa, and all Judah and Benjamin: The LORD is with you while you are with him. If you seek him (<em>tiḏrᵉšûhû</em>), he will be found by you, but if you forsake him (<em>taʿăzᵉḇûhû</em>), he will forsake you.&rdquo; The divine mutuality formula — presence conditioned on covenant faithfulness — is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most economical statement of his entire theology. The conditional is not a threat but a covenant structure: YHWH&rsquo;s presence is with those who seek him; his absence accompanies those who forsake him.</p>",
    "3": "<p>For a long time Israel was without the true God (<em>ʾĕlōhê ʾemet</em>), without a teaching priest (<em>kōhēn môreh</em>), and without law (<em>tôrāh</em>). The triple absence — God, priestly teacher, Torah — describes the period of the judges (the likely referent) or the condition of the northern kingdom. The three together form the covenant community&rsquo;s minimal infrastructure: divine presence, authoritative teaching, written covenant. Without any one, the community is spiritually displaced.</p>",
    "4": "<p>But when in their distress they turned to YHWH, the God of Israel, and sought him (<em>wayyᵉḇaqšūhû</em>), he was found by them. The historical precedent of Judges — the cyclical pattern of apostasy, distress, return, restoration — is cited as proof that the seeking God of Azariah&rsquo;s oracle has a track record. Past seeking-and-finding underwrites the present promise: Azariah is not offering a new covenant principle but reminding Asa of the already-established divine pattern.</p>",
    "5": "<p>In those times there was no peace (<em>šālôm</em>) for the one who went out or the one who came in, for great disturbances (<em>mᵉhûmōt rabbôt</em>) afflicted all the inhabitants of the lands. The description of social chaos during the period of unfaithfulness — instability for traveler and resident alike — draws on the historical memory of the judges era and the political fragmentation of the early monarchy. Peace (<em>šālôm</em>) and rest are gifts of covenant faithfulness; their absence marks covenant disruption.</p>",
    "6": "<p>They were broken in pieces, nation against nation and city against city, for God troubled them with every sort of distress. The universal social disintegration — <em>gôy bᵉgôy ûʿîr bᵉʿîr</em> (nation against nation, city against city) — describes a condition where the bonds of community have dissolved. The attribution to divine causation (<em>ʾĕlōhîm hᵉhāmām bᵉḵol-ṣārāh</em>) is the prophetic historical perspective: social chaos is not merely political failure but covenant consequence.</p>",
    "7": "<p><em>Wᵉʾattem ḥizqû wᵉʾal-yirpû yᵉdêḵem kî yēš śāḵār lipᵉʿullāṯᵉḵem</em> — &ldquo;But you, take courage! Do not let your hands be weak, for your work will be rewarded (<em>śāḵār lipᵉʿullāṯᵉḵem</em>).&rdquo; The closing charge to Asa — positive, forward-looking — balances the historical warning of vv3-6. The three elements: <em>ḥizqû</em> (be strong), <em>ʾal-yirpû</em> (do not be slack), and the promise of reward (<em>śāḵār</em>) for covenant labor. The covenant is not only about avoiding judgment but about receiving the positive fruits of faithfulness.</p>",
    "8": "<p>When Asa hears the words of Azariah the prophet, he takes courage and removes the abominable idols from all the land of Judah and Benjamin and from the cities that he had captured in the hill country of Ephraim — including restoring the altar of YHWH in front of the vestibule. The reform expands beyond Judah&rsquo;s original territory to include the cities captured from the north (ch13) — an all-Israel scope that reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s pan-Israelite vision. The restored altar is the cultic heart of the reform.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Asa gathers all Judah and Benjamin, and those from Ephraim, Manasseh, and Simeon who sojourn with them — for great numbers had deserted (<em>nāpᵉlû</em>) from Israel to him when they saw that YHWH his God was with him. Northerners streaming south to participate in the Judahite reform is the Chronicler&rsquo;s all-Israel motif at its clearest: covenantal faithfulness in the south creates a magnetic draw for those in the north who want to serve YHWH properly. The Chronicler consistently shows the good Judahite king attracting those from the northern tribes who retain covenant loyalty.</p>",
    "10": "<p>They assemble at Jerusalem in the third month of the fifteenth year of Asa&rsquo;s reign. The third month is significant: it corresponds to the time of Shavuot (Pentecost), the feast celebrating the giving of the Torah at Sinai (Exod 19:1). The covenant renewal assembly in the month of Torah-giving links Asa&rsquo;s reform to the original covenant institution — as if the nation is returning to Sinai through its re-commitment in Jerusalem.</p>",
    "11": "<p>They sacrifice to YHWH that day 700 bulls and 7,000 sheep from the spoil they have brought. The sacrificial quantities come directly from the Cushite campaign spoil (14:13-14) — the material blessing of YHWH&rsquo;s victory is immediately consecrated back to YHWH in sacrifice. The cycle is complete: YHWH gives rest and victory; the people give back the fruits of victory as sacrificial worship. Gratitude expressed through sacrifice is the Chronicler&rsquo;s ideal of covenant reciprocity.</p>",
    "12": "<p>They enter into a covenant (<em>wayyāḇōʾû ḇabᵉrît</em>) to seek YHWH (<em>liḏrôš ʾet-YHWH</em>) with all their heart (<em>bᵉḵol-lēḇāḇ</em>) and with all their soul (<em>ûḇᵉḵol-napšām</em>). The covenantal seeking formula combines the two anthropological terms — heart and soul (= Deut 6:5&rsquo;s <em>lēḇāḇ</em> and <em>nepeš</em>) — in the complete self-dedication formula. The covenant renewal is not a legal compliance exercise but a total-self commitment to YHWH.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Whoever would not seek YHWH, the God of Israel, should be put to death, whether young or old, man or woman. The death penalty for covenant apostasy (Deut 13:6-18; 17:12) is the covenant&rsquo;s self-protective provision: the community cannot survive if those who reject YHWH remain within it. The covenant is not a private option but a communal structure; its integrity depends on communal enforcement. The Chronicler records this as Asa&rsquo;s act without editorial comment — covenant renewal involves hard edges.</p>",
    "14": "<p>They swear to YHWH with a loud voice and with shouting and with trumpets and with horns. The multi-sensory, full-community oath — voices, shouting, trumpets, horns — is the public, irreversible declaration of covenant commitment. The loud voice (<em>bᵉqôl gāḏôl</em>) matches the communal scale of the commitment: no one can claim ignorance of what was promised on behalf of all Judah on this day.</p>",
    "15": "<p>All Judah rejoices concerning the oath (<em>wayyiśmᵉḥû kol-Yᵉhûḏāh ʿal-hašŠᵉḇûʿāh</em>), for they have sworn with all their heart and have sought him with all their desire (<em>ûḇᵉḵol-ratṣônām biqqᵉšûhû</em>), and he has been found by them. The joy that accompanies the covenant oath is the Chronicler&rsquo;s affirmation that covenant-keeping is not a burden but a delight. YHWH gives them rest on every side — <em>wayyānaḥ lāhem missāḇîḇ</em> — the direct reward of the seeking-and-finding covenant.</p>",
    "16": "<p>King Asa even removes Maacah his grandmother from being queen mother (<em>gᵉḇîrāh</em>) because she had made a horrifying thing (<em>mipleset</em>) for Asherah. The <em>gᵉḇîrāh</em> (queen mother) was an influential political office in the Judahite monarchy — the king&rsquo;s mother held a court position and wielded real power (1 Kgs 2:19; 15:13). Asa&rsquo;s removal of his grandmother from this office for cultic apostasy demonstrates that the reform extends to the royal family itself; no political relationship immunizes against covenant accountability.</p>",
    "17": "<p>Asa cuts down her Asherah image (<em>ʾet-miplastāh</em>), beats it small, and burns it at the brook Kidron. The destruction formula — cut down, crush, burn — is the Chronicler&rsquo;s standard demolition liturgy for cult objects (cf. Josiah&rsquo;s more elaborate destruction in 34:4-7). The Kidron Valley just east of Jerusalem is the city&rsquo;s waste disposal site for desecrated sacred objects, the place where the unclean is cast (2 Chr 29:16; 30:14; 2 Kgs 23:4-6).</p>",
    "18": "<p>Nevertheless, the high places were not removed from Israel. The qualification is significant: despite the extensive reform, the local high places outside Jerusalem survive into Asa&rsquo;s reign. The repeated note about surviving high places in the Chronicler&rsquo;s good-king evaluations (14:3 says Asa removed them; here it says they were not removed) may reflect different phases of his reign or different regions — high places in the countryside vs. those in the cities. The heart was wholly devoted to YHWH (<em>šālēm lēḇāḇ ʾAsāʾ kol-yāmāyw</em>) — but external cult reform was incomplete.</p>",
    "19": "<p>There was no more war until the thirty-fifth year of Asa&rsquo;s reign. The 35-year span of peace is the Chronicler&rsquo;s record of covenant-faithfulness-producing-rest at its longest: from the covenant renewal (year 15, v10) until year 35, two decades of peace. The extended peace is not merely political fortune but covenant theology — YHWH&rsquo;s gift to the seeking king and people.</p>"
  },
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>In the thirty-sixth year of Asa&rsquo;s reign, Baasha king of Israel comes up against Judah and builds Ramah (<em>Rāmāh</em>) to prevent anyone going out or coming in to Asa king of Judah. The blockade of Ramah (about 5 miles north of Jerusalem) is a choke-point strategy — cutting off Jerusalem from the north. The timing — year 36, after 35 years of peace — marks the moment when the external pressure arrives that will test whether Asa&rsquo;s covenant faithfulness translates to crisis-trust or political calculation.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Asa takes silver and gold from the treasuries of YHWH&rsquo;s house and the king&rsquo;s house and sends them to Ben-hadad king of Syria at Damascus to buy a military alliance. The transaction is precisely described: temple treasure + royal treasure = Syrian military service. The Chronicler&rsquo;s readers would immediately recognize the problem: Asa is using YHWH&rsquo;s own treasury to fund a political solution that bypasses YHWH&rsquo;s protection. The temple treasure was given in trust; spending it on a foreign alliance is a form of <em>maʿal</em> (unfaithfulness).</p>",
    "3": "<p><em>Bᵉrît bênî ûḇênêḵā ûḇên-ʾāḇî ûḇên-ʾāḇîḵā hinnēh šālāḥtî lᵉḵā kesep ûzāhāḇ lēḵ hāper ʾet-bᵉrîtᵉḵā ʾet-Baeʿšāʾ melek Yiśrāʾēl wᵉyaʿal mēʿālay</em> — &ldquo;Let there be a covenant between me and you, as between my father and your father.&rdquo; Asa uses covenant language (<em>bᵉrît</em>) with a foreign king — the same language used for Israel&rsquo;s covenant with YHWH. The irony is sharp: the king who entered a covenant with YHWH (15:12) now enters a covenant with Aram using YHWH&rsquo;s money to fund it.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Ben-hadad listens to Asa and sends his commanders against the cities of Israel, striking Ijon, Dan, Abel-maim, and all the store cities of Naphtali. The strategy works militarily: the Syrian assault on the northern cities forces Baasha to withdraw from Ramah. Asa has solved the immediate military problem. But the Chronicler&rsquo;s theology requires that we read the military success as a spiritual failure: solving the problem by the wrong means is still the wrong means.</p>",
    "5": "<p>When Baasha hears it, he stops building Ramah and abandons his work. The tactical withdrawal signals the success of Asa&rsquo;s Syrian strategy — from a purely military standpoint, the diplomacy worked. But the Chronicler has already established the evaluative framework: what matters is not whether the strategy succeeded but whether Asa sought YHWH. The success of ungodly means does not validate them.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Asa takes the stones and timber of Ramah that Baasha had been using and builds with them Geba and Mizpah. The repurposed materials — stones of the enemy&rsquo;s fortification becoming the materials of Asa&rsquo;s own — is a small pragmatic victory. But in the Chronicler&rsquo;s narrative it reads as a footnote: Asa builds with Baasha&rsquo;s stones while the deeper spiritual deficit goes unaddressed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Hanani the seer comes to Asa and says: <em>bᵉhišŠāʿănᵉḵā ʿal-melek ʾĂrām wᵉlōʾ nišŠāʿantā ʿal-YHWH ʾĕlōheḵā ʿal-kēn niplat ḥêl melek ʾĂrām miyyāḏeḵā</em> — &ldquo;Because you relied on the king of Syria and did not rely on YHWH your God, the army of the king of Syria has escaped you.&rdquo; The prophetic verb <em>šāʿan</em> (to rely/lean on) from 14:11 appears now in its negative form: Asa who once relied on YHWH now relies on Ben-hadad. The escape of the Syrian army — which could have been captured had YHWH fought — is what Asa has forfeited by his alliance.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Were not the Cushites and the Libyans a huge army with chariots and horsemen exceedingly many? Yet because you relied on YHWH (<em>nišŠāʿantā bYHWH</em>), he gave them into your hand. The prophet reminds Asa of his own history — the Cushite victory of ch14, explicitly cited — to make the contrast concrete: same king, different crisis, different response, different outcome. YHWH&rsquo;s track record for those who trust him is the basis of the rebuke: you already know what happens when you rely on YHWH; why did you abandon that knowledge?</p>",
    "9": "<p><em>Kî YHWH ʿênāyw mᵉšōṭᵉṭôt bᵉḵol-hāʾāreṣ lᵉhitḥazzēq ʿim-lᵉḇāḇām šālēm ʾēlāyw</em> — &ldquo;For the eyes of the LORD run to and fro throughout the whole earth, to give strong support to those whose heart is blameless/whole toward him.&rdquo; This is one of the Chronicler&rsquo;s most theologically concentrated statements: divine omniscience (<em>ʿênāyw mᵉšōṭᵉṭôt</em> = eyes running to and fro) is not neutral surveillance but active searching for whole-hearted devotion in order to give strength (<em>hitḥazzēq</em>) to those who have it. The verse appears in Zech 4:10 (&ldquo;seven eyes of YHWH which range through the whole earth&rdquo;). You have acted foolishly in this — <em>niśkaltā ʿal-zōʾt</em> — the prophetic verdict on pragmatic faithlessness.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Asa is angry with the seer and puts him in the stocks (<em>bêt hammahpeket</em>), for he is enraged (<em>zāʿap</em>) at him because of this. Asa becomes the first Judahite king in Chronicles to imprison a prophet — the same movement that Ahab made against Micaiah (18:25-26). The imprisonment of the prophetic word is the political expression of spiritual refusal: if I cannot silence YHWH&rsquo;s word, I can at least silence YHWH&rsquo;s messenger. Asa also inflicts cruelties on some of the people at the same time.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The acts of Asa, from first to last, are written in the book of the kings of Judah and Israel. The Chronicler&rsquo;s source citation here is transitional — the good and the bad, the early faithfulness and the late failure, are all on record. The citation of a single source encompassing both &ldquo;from first to last&rdquo; is the Chronicler&rsquo;s way of acknowledging that Asa&rsquo;s story is mixed: it cannot be summarized as simply success or failure.</p>",
    "12": "<p>In the thirty-ninth year of his reign Asa is diseased in his feet (<em>wᵉḥālāh ʾAsāʾ beraglāyw</em>) — severely — yet even in his disease he did not seek YHWH (<em>lōʾ-dāraš ʾet-YHWH</em>), but sought help from physicians (<em>birōpᵉʾîm</em>). The escalating pattern: in year 36, instead of trusting YHWH he trusts Aram; in year 39, instead of seeking YHWH for healing he seeks only physicians. The Chronicler does not condemn physicians as such — the critique is the &ldquo;only&rdquo;: Asa sought physicians and did not seek YHWH. The failure of <em>dāraš</em> (seeking) runs from political crisis to physical illness.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Asa slept with his fathers, dying in the forty-first year of his reign. The 41-year reign — one of the longest in Chronicles — ends with two years of diseased feet. The death of the great reforming king in his disease, without having returned to YHWH, is the Chronicler&rsquo;s most sobering statement about covenant momentum: even the best reforms cannot carry a king through decades of accumulated drift. The whole heart (15:17) can be lost piece by piece.</p>",
    "14": "<p>They bury him in the tomb he had cut for himself in the city of David. They lay him on a bier filled with spices and various kinds of blended myrrh and make a very great fire in his honor. The royal burial with spices and a great fire of honor was a mark of high esteem — the same honor was given to Asa&rsquo;s father Asa (actually: see 2 Chr 21:19 for the contrast with Jehoram who received no fire). The elaborate funeral honors indicate that despite his late-reign failures, Asa&rsquo;s positive legacy was remembered and honored by the people.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>Jehoshaphat his son reigns in his place and strengthens himself against Israel. Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s reign (872-848 BC) begins with military consolidation — he stations troops in all the fortified cities of Judah and sets garrisons in the land and in the cities of Ephraim that Asa his father had captured. The inheritance of captured Ephraimite territory (from Asa&rsquo;s victory of 15:8) and its further garrisoning signals a Judahite sphere of influence that extends into what was once the northern kingdom.</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jehoshaphat walks in the earlier ways of his father David (<em>bᵉdarkê ḏāwîḏ āḇîw hārīʾšōnîm</em>) — &ldquo;the first ways of David&rdquo; — not seeking the Baals but seeking the God of his father David and walking in his commandments. The reference to David&rsquo;s &ldquo;earlier ways&rdquo; (the ways of his early faithful period) as the standard against which Jehoshaphat is measured is a subtle reminder that even David had earlier and later ways; Jehoshaphat is measured against David at his best.</p>",
    "3": "<p>YHWH is with Jehoshaphat because he walks in the earlier ways of his father David. The divine presence (<em>YHWH ʿimmô</em>) as the consequence of covenant faithfulness is the Chronicler&rsquo;s thesis statement for the reign: everything that follows — the tribute, the armies, the teaching mission — flows from the prior reality of YHWH&rsquo;s presence. He does not seek the Baals (<em>wᵉlōʾ ḏāraš labbᵉʿālîm</em>) — the negative form of <em>dāraš</em> making the positive all the more apparent.</p>",
    "4": "<p>His heart is courageous in the ways of YHWH (<em>wayyigbah libbô bᵉdarḵê YHWH</em>). <em>Gābah lēḇāḇ</em> (the heart being high/lifted) is ambiguous in Hebrew: it can mean proud/arrogant (Prov 18:12; Ezek 28:2, 17 — the sin of pride) or courageous/bold (as here — positive). The Chronicler uses it positively when the elevated heart is in the ways of YHWH; negatively when it is in self-congratulation (26:16; 32:25). And he removes the high places and the Asherim from Judah — the reform initiative continuing from Asa.</p>",
    "5": "<p>All Judah brings tribute to Jehoshaphat, and he has great riches and honor. The tribute and prosperity that follow covenant faithfulness are the material expression of the blessing promised in Deuteronomy: the obedient king who keeps the covenant receives the covenant rewards (Deut 28:1-14). Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s prosperity is not commercial acumen but covenant fruit.</p>",
    "6": "<p>His heart is emboldened in the ways of YHWH (<em>wayyigbah libbô bᵉdarḵê YHWH</em>) — he also removes the high places and the Asherim from Judah. The repetition of the <em>gābah lēḇāḇ</em> phrase from v4 and the repeated note about high places and Asherim signals a sustained reform momentum, not a single event. The Chronicler is constructing a picture of a king whose internal disposition produces continuous external action.</p>",
    "7": "<p>In the third year of his reign he sends his officials — Ben-hail, Obadiah, Zechariah, Nethanel, Micaiah — to teach in the cities of Judah. The teaching mission is a distinctive Chronicler initiative: Jehoshaphat commissions a reform that is not merely cultic (destroying altars) but educational (teaching the Torah). The officials are sent first — the civil leadership — establishing the institutional framework for the teaching.</p>",
    "8": "<p>With them are Levites: Shemaiah, Nethiah, Zebadiah, Asahel, Shemiramoth, Jehonathan, Adonijah, Tobijah, and Tob-adonijah the Levites; and with them Elishama and Jehoram the priests. The teaching team — five officials, nine Levites, two priests — reflects the Chronicler&rsquo;s vision of layered educational ministry: civic leaders, Levitical teachers, and priestly authorities cooperating in national Torah education. The specificity of all sixteen names gives the mission a historical weight that resists symbolic reduction.</p>",
    "9": "<p>They teach in Judah, having the book of the law of YHWH with them (<em>ûḇêhem sēper tôrat-YHWH</em>). They go throughout all the cities of Judah and teach among the people. The written Torah is the content of the teaching — <em>sēper tôrat-YHWH</em> (the book of the law of YHWH), the same phrase used for the discovered law-scroll under Josiah (34:14-15). The Levitical teaching mission that Jehoshaphat establishes gives every city access to YHWH&rsquo;s word; this is the OT precursor to the synagogue institution of Torah reading and teaching.</p>",
    "10": "<p>The fear of YHWH (<em>paḥaḏ YHWH</em>) falls on all the kingdoms of the lands around Judah — they make no war against Jehoshaphat. The political peace that follows the teaching mission is theologically attributed: it is YHWH&rsquo;s fear that keeps the surrounding nations at bay, not military superiority. The teaching of Torah throughout Judah produces a national character that radiates divine authority — visible enough to the surrounding nations to deter aggression.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Some of the Philistines bring tribute to Jehoshaphat and silver as a present; the Arabians also bring flocks: 7,700 rams and 7,700 male goats. The Philistines bringing tribute is a historic reversal: the perennial enemy of Israel since the judges era now submits economically to the covenant king. The specific numbers (7,700 rams + 7,700 goats) reflect the Chronicler&rsquo;s love of symmetric quantities for divine-gift catalogues.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Jehoshaphat grows steadily greater — <em>wayyēleḵ Yᵉhôšāpāṭ gāḏēl wᵉhaʿāleh</em> (he went, becoming progressively greater and going up) — and he builds fortresses and store cities in Judah. The progressive growth formula (<em>gāḏēl wᵉhaʿāleh</em>) is the Chronicler&rsquo;s idiom for sustained covenant prosperity — not a single achievement but a trajectory of increasing blessing. The store cities are both economic infrastructure and military logistics.</p>",
    "13": "<p>He has large supplies in the cities of Judah, and warriors, mighty men of valor, in Jerusalem. The combination of material supply and military strength is the prosperity formula for a covenant king: YHWH gives both physical resources and human capacity. Neither is achieved independent of YHWH&rsquo;s blessing; both are gifts to the faithful king.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The roll of the army by fathers&rsquo; houses: from Judah, commanders of thousands — Adnah the commander with 300,000 mighty men of valor; besides him Jehohanan the commander with 280,000. The military census of Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s army (vv14-19) demonstrates the strength that comes with covenant faithfulness. This census, unlike David&rsquo;s sinful census (1 Chr 21), is a presentation of divinely given strength, not a self-reliant audit.</p>",
    "15": "<p>And besides him Amasiah son of Zichri, a volunteer for the service of YHWH (<em>hammitnaddēḇ laYHWH</em>), with 200,000 mighty men of valor. The phrase <em>hammitnaddēḇ laYHWH</em> (voluntary for/dedicated to YHWH) uses the same reflexive <em>nādaḇ</em> verb that describes the freewill offerings in 1 Chr 29 — the warrior&rsquo;s dedication to YHWH&rsquo;s service is analogous to the worshiper&rsquo;s freewill offering. The army is an act of worship.</p>",
    "16": "<p>From Benjamin: Eliada, a mighty warrior, with 200,000 men armed with bow and shield; and besides him Jehozabad with 180,000 equipped for war. Benjamin&rsquo;s contribution — 380,000 — adds to Judah&rsquo;s 780,000 for a total of 1,160,000 warriors. The enumeration of Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s army by tribe and unit parallels David&rsquo;s military organization in 1 Chr 27, presenting Jehoshaphat as a new David in his military and administrative capacity.</p>",
    "17": "<p>These were in the service of the king, besides those whom the king had placed in the fortified cities throughout all Judah. The distinction between the standing army in Jerusalem and the garrison forces throughout Judah indicates a multi-tier military structure: a central strike force plus distributed territorial defense. The military infrastructure is both the sign and the means of YHWH&rsquo;s protection given to the faithful king.</p>",
    "18": "<p>Jehoshaphat had great riches and honor — <em>wᵉhāyāh lîhôšāpāṭ ʿōšer wᵉḵāḇôḏ lārōb</em> — and he allied himself with Ahab through marriage. This verse, the Chronicler&rsquo;s transition into the Ramoth-gilead narrative (ch18), places the Ahab alliance immediately after the catalog of Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s blessings. The juxtaposition is deliberate: the greatest king since Asa, with unparalleled wealth, armies, and honor — yet about to compromise all of it through a marriage alliance with the apostate north. Prosperity without vigilance creates vulnerability.</p>",
    "19": "<p>The army roles are distributed: some stationed in Jerusalem, some throughout the fortified cities. The final verse of ch17 is both a completion of the military census and a transition: Jehoshaphat&rsquo;s well-organized kingdom, with its armies in place, is about to face the test of chapter 18 — whether the military strength and covenant faithfulness of the first part of his reign will survive the political entanglement with Ahab.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    existing = load_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles')
    merge_comm(existing, CHRON2_CONTEXT_13_17)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '2chronicles', existing)
    print('2 Chronicles 13-17 context layer written.')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
